<p><a name="Origins" id="Origins"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Moksha&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Origins">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Origins</span></h2>
<p>It is highly probable that the concept of moksha (along with <a href="/wiki/Karma" title="Karma">karma</a>, <a href="/wiki/Reincarnation" title="Reincarnation">reincarnation</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Samsara" title="Samsara" class="mw-redirect">samsara</a>) was first developed in India by non-<a href="/wiki/Indo-Aryan_peoples" title="Indo-Aryan peoples">Aryan</a> people outside of the <a href="/wiki/Caste_system_in_India" title="Caste system in India">caste system</a> whose spiritual ideas greatly influenced later Indian religious thought. Buddhism and Jainism are continuations of this tradition, and the early Upanishadic movement was influenced by it. Reincarnation was likely adopted from this religious culture by <a href="/wiki/Vedic_Brahmanism" title="Vedic Brahmanism" class="mw-redirect">Brahmin</a> orthodoxy. Brahmins wrote the earliest recorded scriptures containing these ideas in the early <a href="/wiki/Upanishads" title="Upanishads">Upanishads</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6" title=""><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a name="Hinduism" id="Hinduism"></a></p>
