</table>
<div class="rellink noprint relarticle mainarticle">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Moksa_(Jainism)" title="Moksa (Jainism)">Moksa (Jainism)</a></div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Jainism" title="Jainism">Jainism</a>, Moksa and <a href="/wiki/Nirvana_(Jainism)" title="Nirvana (Jainism)">Nirvana (Jainism)</a> are not the same. Nirvana is when the soul is passed from one body to another. When a soul (atman) achieves Moksa, it is released from the cycle of births and deaths, and achieves its pure self. It then becomes a <a href="/wiki/Siddha" title="Siddha">Siddha</a> (literally means one who has accomplished his ultimate objective).</p>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Jainism" title="Jainism">Jainism</a>, attaining Moksa requires annihilation of all karmas, good and bad; because if karma is left, it must bear fruit.</p>
<p><a name="See_also" id="See_also"></a></p>
